metadata.name: Obscure Archive #75
metadata.description:
Tabula rasa - we are all born without mental condition built-in, therefore knowledge and emotions come from experience.

As we grow up, emotions and feelings come to us naturally. Joy, sadness, anger, tranquility, confusion - to name a few, all these emotions makes us who we are today consciously or subconsciously. Yet, negative emotions are easier to remember and sticks longer compared to the positive ones.

Though, some people are lucky enough to be able to express their emotions freely to their surrounding, letting others know what they're feeling & what they've been through. While some other finds it harder to let go of those negative emotions. Wanting them to be gone but, alas, they can't find the right conditions to do so. Or even worse, these emotions get mixed up and tangled with their thoughts and memories making it harder to read or express.

__________

Obscure Archive is trying to capture what I (or maybe, you too) have been feeling constantly. These negative emotions is expressed and written as the text within the artwork, with the supergraphic representing thoughts & memories that we have. Some of the artwork has no overlay, just like those who can express their emotions freely. While some other have a completely different overlay, with messy text and supergraphic representing the concealment & entangled thoughts that make the emotions harder to read.

__________

made with ❤️ and p5js

metadata.name: Oddball #19
metadata.description:
Oddball is an expansion of the piece I created for day 7 of Genuary 2023. The prompt: Sample a color palette from your favorite movie/album cover. All seven palettes in this project were sampled from the album cover for Insolito by Tipper (https://tipper.bandcamp.com/album/insolito). 

The project title is a play on insolito meaning "unusual" and the featured bubble-like cellular noise. These bubbles are used to warp low-frequency simplex noise. When combined with the vibrant palettes, striking psychedelic patterns appear.

Controls:

[space] or click to toggle animation
[r] to reset animation to static view
[s] to save as 4000x4000 PNG
[t] to toggle paper texture

metadata.name: The Gap #15
metadata.description:
The Gap is an impressive generative art collection that showcases nature in its purest and most elemental form. At the center of the piece is a break between two walls of ice.
 The break appears to have been created by relentless ice pressure, and its shape and size are a result of the complex interaction between water, ice, and underlying geology.
But what truly captures the viewer's attention are the brilliant colors surrounding the break. The sky is depicted in a warm, brilliant color, while the break is depicted in a cold, brilliant color. These flat, saturated colors create a striking contrast that makes the break stand out in the landscape. Together, these colors create a vibrant and evocative atmosphere that invites viewers to dive into the landscape and explore its details.
In summary, The Gap is a unique work that combines technology and nature to create a stunning and impactful visual experience. With its contrast of warm and cold, brilliant flat colors, this work is a statement about the strength and simplicity of nature, and a call to action to protect our planet.

metadata.name: Perpendicular Inhabitation #368
metadata.description:
'Perpendicular Inhabitation' is a generative collection exploring the relationship between the urban landscape and the human experience, particularly feelings of nostalgia and more specifically 'anemoia' : the feeling of nostalgia for a time or place that we may not have actually experienced first hand. 

Despite depicting a stylised modern architectural language, at its core the collection serves as a homage to 1980s Japan, an era of unprecedented prosperity that left a lasting impression on the music and artwork of the time. Through the use of carefully created palettes and composition, the outputs intend to evoke feelings of optimism, while guiding viewers to consider why the essence of this era is so alluring in the present day as it continues to influence and inspire contemporary art.

The use of exaggerated perpendicular verticals, as well as the heavily foreshortened mountain ranges present in some outputs, convey a sense of hope and possibility for the future. What does it feel like to hope and dream in the city? To look up and be filled with a sense of wonder from the built environment around you?

This project has been created with print in mind at a ratio of 3:4

It is recommended to examine your outputs at full size in order to enjoy them to the fullest.

You are encouraged to return often to notice things you may not have seen previously.

Generated with code using p5.js

Images are generated at 2400 x 3200 px. 

To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

Depending on the complexity of each output, please wait up to 10 seconds for the image generation to complete.

metadata.name: RAUSCH #109
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________
RAUSCH Controls:

Animation: 
• ‘1 - 2 - 3 - 4’ animate views
• 'MouseClick' pause/play animation

Functions:
(press key & wait)
• 'F' 24 FPS
• 'B' b/w mode 

Resize Canvas:
(press key & wait)
• '6' Portrait A4 - 1000x1414
• '7' Landscape 16:9 - 1920x1080
• '8' Portrait 9:16 - 1080x1920
• '9' Square 1:1 - 1024x1024
• 'DoubleClick' Fullscreen

Save & Export Image:
• 'S' save a .png of in current resolution

Save & Export GIF:
• 'G' save a 1-2 sec. seamless loop .gif of current view 
• 'P' save a 12-24 sec. seamless loop .gif of all the views
• 'T’ scale down current resolution, save a 12 sec. seamless loop .gif

Steps to save a gif/png :
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• resize canvas with 6,7,8, or 9 to your desired aspect ratio (wait)
• press S,G or P to save & download (wait) 
• enjoy RAUSCH :)

Save & Export GIF for social media sharing:
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• press T or G wait for recalculation & download. 
• enjoy RAUSCH 
• post on Twitter ;)
__________________________________________________

This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy RAUSCH on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

metadata.name: Growth v02 #105
metadata.description:
Growth patterns, version 2. January 2022
Edition of 512

Growth v02 is an generative exploration of patterns in the style of William Morris' iconic wallpaper designs from the 1800s. The code for the Growth series was originally designed to create plausible road networks but has been rewritten to create more organic curved forms. Created with p5js.

'space' to pause the simulation
'h' to toggle to higher res (increases canvas size but runs slower: great for screengrabs)
'r' to reset the seed (some features are locked to the original hash)
's' to save an image to disk
All generated patterns are tile-able horizontally and vertically.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

This project relies heavily on randomly generated values. It has been thoroughly tested. However, there is always the chance that the wrong combination of randomness can create less-compelling growth. If you feel you version is not living up to the potential promised with this piece, please email me.

metadata.name: Badgirs City #24
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: Resilience  #98
metadata.description:
Resilience is a collection of endless architectures.
In a resilient generative system composed of multiple compatible parts, real-time information exchange enables open reconfigurations and continuous discrete adjustments. Sometimes vague and fuzzy, sometimes real and tangible, they reveal different readings of architectural complexity and scale: from city plans to floor plans and details to sections and elevations.

Resilience comes in a variety of polychrome palettes, ascii glyphs, and styles. 
To enjoy it in full-screen mode, press the left mouse button in live mode, for a monochrome look press 'b'. Made with P5js.

Resilience Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022
